ratings.question_text: Your level of engagement with the course was:
What is your overall assessment of this course?
The course was well organized to facilitate student learning.
I received clear feedback that improved my learning.
Relative to other courses you have taken at Yale, the level of intellectual challenge of this course was:
Relative to other courses you have taken at Yale, the workload of this course was:

narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I learned a lot about different histories of race, colonialism, and migration through this course.
Learned alot about different racial groups

I found that the course talked about interesting concepts and themes, but I didn't find myself learning very much. It felt like much of the class was just hearing and discussing global issues related to ER&M without really analyzing them beyond saying that they were bad.
Good

I received a survey view of the field of study that is ethnicity, race, and migration at Yale. I had the opportunity to reexamine and reconsider historical events and processes in a new light. I read a variety of primary and secondary sources, and practiced my writing through synthesizing and responding to these sources.

Through this course I got an introduction into ER&M and race studies in general. I learned about important catastrophic events in world history, and how they affect governments and populations today. I also learned about the importance of music, art, and other forms of expression, as well as how to write and talk about them through a social justice lens.
I learned a lot about the history of race, ethnicity, and migration. I also learned how these concepts affect current day. I also improved my skills in analyzing readings and works of art.

An overview of ethnic studies and important subfields like Indigenous studies and queer of color critique. Important ways of thinking about history, politics, and day-to-day life that's very different from what they teach you in grade school (in a very good way).
I learned about how racial difference affects the lives and histories of various racial and ethnic groups, along with how colonialism and capitalism affect these differences.
I learned about how colonial processes have cemented conceptions of race and ethnicity around the world.

I learned about the fundamental themes and historical events that have led to the study of ethnicity, race, and migration. I gained insight on terms such as race and ethnicity that are far more complex than the very definition itself. The course made me question the history I had been told my whole life.

This course is a great introduction the baseline issues of critical race theory and the hidden histories of America's racist and colonial past. I would recommend it to everyone who has yet to educate themselves on things like this.
knowledge about various critical theories and history of ethnicity, race, and migration.
I think this is the perfect intro course for the major, especially if they have no previous exposure to world events involving POC.
This course went over very basic and introductory themes in Indigenous, Black, and other studies. I thought it would be more in depth, but it felt a little surface level.
I learned about history and racial processes through the perspective of BIPOC. One piece of knowledge that has particularly stick with me is the difference between the post colony and decolonization.
This course was a great intro into the world of er&m studies, and it taught me new ways to think about and conceive of important historical and political concepts
Overview of ethnic and racial histories as well as social contexts of concepts such as (de)colonialism, indigeneity, racial exclusion, migration, etc.
I learned how to be critical with the world around me in terms of colonialism and greed and I learned how to connect contemporary art and literature to historical events relating to ethnic relations.
This course gives a broad overview of many different topics in ER&M. You get to study different ethnic groups, different time periods, and read a great selection of authors.
Learned about various concepts relating to racial politics both nationally and globally.
I learned a lot about instiutional systems of oppresion
The course seeks to understand the complex cultural practices and ideologies that have permitted the concept of race to function as a central organizing element for societies structured in dominance.

I learned how to think about art and media in connection to topics in Ethnicity, Race, and Migration.
I learned important concepts and definitions to further apply to my studies in the field. 
Overall just a broad survey of topics across racial identities, ethnicities, and sexualities.
I was able to learn how to engage critically with the material presented, I learned how to read and think about what was being presented
This course offers a great survey and introduction to the themes and ideas within the ER&M major. You learn about migration, genocide, indigeneity, colonialism, etc.
I learned some of the basics around the topics in this class, and a lot of theoretical frameworks that are applicable to current events.

I learned a lot about episodes of world/U.S. history that they typically shy away from in regular HS classes, as well as how to rethink a lot of the racial and capitalist processes that are ingrained in our society
Terminology for ER&M, using theorists ideas to inform my understanding of things, how to right analytically as opposed to creatively
Early ethnic and migration patterns and forced migration were critical in understanding race relations nowadays.
I gained a broad overview of race and immigration in US history
This course was a prerequisite for the ER&M major. This course allowed me to gain a more expansive knowledge of some of the topics included within the field of study.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: I enjoyed the section discussions and most of the readings from this course as I found they were really engaging. Although I enjoyed lecture, I sometimes found it difficult to follow because we hopped around from theme to theme quite a bit and I didn't feel like I really got a good introduction to where we were moving next at the start of each class. I also wish there had been more of a visible thread from topic to topic.

I think the course should aim to dive a little deeper into some of the topics. I understand that it's an introductory course, but I think that it can remain a broad, intro course while still diving deeper into a slightly smaller number of examples and ideas.

I really enjoyed the guest lecturers that were brought in. They were all very knowledgeable and engaging, and it was super interesting to hear what they had to say.

Professor Camacho was extremely thoughtful, caring, and knowledgeable about all the topics discussed throughout the course. Her intuitive understanding of the course material provided all of us with a great insight into the course materials. However, I hope in the future that she placed more information on the class presentations, and that she felt more free to not use the standard script for presenting.
Not sure tbh but my level of engagement could've been higher

The readings for this course are very good. Though some weeks I was unable to find the time to work through the readings, in weeks in which I did I always came away with interesting insights. The lectures were always well-prepared, though I sometimes found the delivery to drag a bit. The sections felt a little inconsistent/disorganized, perhaps as a result of a lack of guidance given to the TFs on how section should be conducted. The class was not a lot of work - the few assignments we had were quite painless, and in some cases enjoyable and reflective to do. However, as a result of the ease of the course, students in the class tended to phone it in; during lectures, hardly any students beyond the first couple of rows were paying any attention, making participation during lectures and sections feel awkward and forced. I got the impression that plenty of students were there not to learn but to get an easy credit, which I found discouraging.

One thing I think could be done to improve the course is to make the key concepts more explicitly written out on Canvas or on lecture guides. Sometimes during exam periods I felt like I was searching to ensure that I included all the key terms. Section was definitely a strength of this course and Katy Maldonado Dominguez was awesome.
I thought a strength were the assignments, readings, and class discussions. I thought a weakness was that lectures went a bit slowly and there weren't enough slides.

Strengths: Extremely low workload. Fascinating and well-chosen readings. Amazing lectures from both Camacho and the numerous guest lecturers (other ER&M professors). Camacho and all the TFs are so caring and understanding. Weaknesses: Honestly can't think of any. This isn't really a weakness, but for those who don't do the readings, you can still get by easily in the class; you'll just be missing out on stuff that's important not for this class but just important in general.

Strengths: Guest lecturers were often invited. It was nice to see the insights each lecturer brought.
Weaknesses: Slides arent very informative and they are hard to read (ex. black words on brown background).

Strengths: guest lectures, interesting material
Areas of improvement: more engaging lectures or shorter lecture time
Lectures were boring and sometimes it was hard to follow since the powerpoints werent posted and were mostly quotes or pictures.
A strength is that the course is very interesting in content and has a very manageable workload. However, the only weakness is the lecture itself, which can be very dense and hard to follow.

The lectures not being recorded and lecture attendance being such a high percentage of the grade was not the most conducive to accessibility, especially as everyone tried to navigate COVID-19 this semesteralthough, we were never penalized for illness related absences in section, this could not be well communicated for lecture. I really enjoyed the guest lecturers, and I feel that Professor Camacho chose an interesting and valuable variety of speakers to come impart their specific wisdoms and guidance.
Guest lecturers were great. Readings were really good. I found Professor Camacho's lectures boring and wished they covered more content or expounded more on the readings.

A strength was the amount of guest lecturers we had. Those were the most engaging days. A weakness was a lack of niche topics/conversation. Since it was an intro course, we hopped around a lot rather than spending a longer period of time on subjects that deserve it.
The readings for the course were very interesting but lectures dragged on for a while and I never became engaged in them. I think the guest lecturers were interesting as well.

Strengths: A large variety of topics were covered and the guest lecturers were amazing. 
Weaknesses: Readings were too long for an introductory course and felt very heavy. These reading sometimes felt disconnected from class as well as it wasn't always tied in to lecture. The lecture portion of this course also felt very detached as we were often talked at for long periods of time with no engaging powerpoint to accompany the talk that made it hard to follow along.
The readings are extremely interesting and you learn so much from them. There arent many things that count toward the grade which can be both good and bad.
All of the content was very interesting, and I thought all the assignments were fun and very fair. But I did think that lectures and sections could feel a bit slow sometimes.

Strengths: You learn the foundations of ER&M studies, including racism, slavery, human rights, genocide, etc.

Weaknesses: If you are a person of color, you most likely are already aware of and have been directly affected by the issues taught in this course.

It covered so many topic and brought in many guest speakers (which I really really enjoyed). Weaknesses were that the first half of the semester just seemed like very basic stuff, histories of slavery, race, indigenous thought, and didn't frame these concepts in a new way which made the class pretty redundant and boring. If there was a way to introduce these concepts in a more engaging way that is not always a lecture, such as how the second half of the semester was conducted with analyzing music and art, that would be more interesting. It would also be interesting to focus on specific indigenous communities and their values, but also emphasize the contrast of values within indigenous communities.
The strengths are the readings which were so enriching and amazing, such so that I never missed a reading. A weakness is that it was organized in an odd way.

This course is a great introduction into the field. The only improvement I could suggest is to make the lectures more compelling and tie in the readings more. The lectures are great but could use more energy.
Lots of different topics in the syllabus
This course needs to have more timely feedback and more engagement with the material

Strengths: discussion sections are required for students to gain a greater and in-depth understanding of the content, without it one would be lost; guest lecturers are often invited to share their expertise
Weaknesses: lectures can feel long

I think the course could be improved a lot with more visually engaging lectures. Professor Camacho has a lot of really meaningful, interesting things to say, but it is really difficult to pay attention without consistent visual engagement. I also did not think the global playlists assignment was that meaningful.

strengths: the content is absolutely great, i think the syllabus is very strong and this is aided by the TAs and the guest speakers
weaknesses: the lecturing style is extremely lackluster, there is pretty much no engagement at all by the peers sitting around me, many not even attending most of the time.

The course looks at a large range of topics, which is great for a survey class. But this also means that sometimes it felt like discussions and lectures lacked focus/continuity. Otherwise, the lectures, activities, and sections were all organized well to optimize learning.
The content is great, and so is Professor Camacho

strengths: Professor Camacho is very kind and understanding, TAs are very supportive, lecture topics and readings are really thought-provoking and important for students to read, assignments are relatively straightforward, guest speakers all bring interesting perspectives Weaknesses: it takes a while to get feedback back, you need to be intrinsically motivated to follow along lectures and listen closely

strength: interesting course content

weakness: lectures were not engaging
Weakness: engaging course readings did not align with less engaging lectures, topics like gay liberation were not covered
The content was great, but I wasnt always fond of Professor Camachos speech/TED-talk-like teaching method. It was hard to distinguish relevant information from fluff.
this course (especially the first half of it) seemed designed more for white people since it covered very basics that people of color would already know from their experiences with opression

Strength: variety of materials we engaged with, such as film, photography, music, art, poetry, etc. The guest speakers were also fantastic!

Weakness: low engagement with the class and nearly no participation
The strengths of this course are the overall content covered and the ways they are presented. The course could be improved by being more engaging.

Strength: interesting topics, supportive environment
Weakness: lectures felt a bit long (shortening class period?), it also felt very general

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: I would recommend this course if you are curious about the ER&M major. While it is quite different from the possible seminars or other lectures you might take in the major, I think the material you are exposed to is very helpful and emblematic of the way of thinking in the major.
I enjoyed the course. I found the topics interesting and the course wasn't very difficult. I would recommend the course to anyone who is interested in exploring the field of ER&M.
Not really -- didn't find it particularly engaging
I would recommend this course to a student looking for a relatively painless credit, who is excited to learn about ethnicity, race, and migration.
Yes I would recommend this course to another student. The subject matter was engaging and important, and conversations in discussion and during lecture were enlightening.
I would recommend this course if you're interested in these topics. However, keep in mind that it's pretty broad and doesn't go super into depth.
Yes, without reservation. This is a course *every person* at Yale should take -- especially white folks.

No, I would not recommend this course. Its hard to follow along during the lectures, which is bad because they talk about material not covered in the readings. Because its hard to follow along, the class is really boring, and I found myself zoning out on most days.
Yes! It is quite manageable, the assignments are genuinely enjoyable, and sections are very comfortable spaces in which to discuss ideas of race and ethnicity.
I would only recommend this class to students interested in the ER&M major. If not, this class isnt for you.
I would. I think ER&M is invaluable to our school and to anyone's education.

No. I typically like humanities classes even though I do not major in them, but this class was not engaging. There were too many topics for us to cover any one of them in much depth. The readings were usually very good but sometimes used so much technical language that I struggled to follow. Discussion was very boring and dominated by humanities students who used big words.
I do if youre someone who doesnt have an experience as a person of color or had to study the history as much.
I would not recommend this course to another student. I think there are more interesting ER&M courses that Yale has to offer.

Yes! While I have my reservations about how the course is taught, it is overall a great class that introduces you to a wide range of topics. Professor Camacho is very knowledgeable and does have a genuine care for her students.
Yes I definitely would recommend this course! The content is truly mind blowing and the readings are very interesting.
No. I would only recommend this course (ERM 200 with Prof. Camacho) to ER&M majors b/c it's a requirement. I believe the surface-level nature of this course, as well as the
Yes absolutely. I think the assignments in this course were very well designed to facilitate real student learning, and all of the concepts are super important.
If you do not intend to major in ER&M or are more interested in learning about a specific topic in the major, Id recommend taking an ER&M seminar rather than this intro course.

This course was ok, I don't think I would necessarily recommend it to someone with knowledge of basic race history, but I would recommend it to someone who does not know anything since it is a very baseline class.
I would still recommend this course to others because it puts a lot of things into perspective and taught me a lot about the world around me.
Yes it was a good survey course.
This class is pretty much a gut, but you still learn some stuff. It is both fun and interesting without stressing too much
If you need it as a requirement for the ER&M major or as an easy HU credit, sure. Otherwise, there are much more intellectually-rewarding and intersing courses out there.

Unless you plan on majoring in ER&M, I don't know that I would. I think there are seminars/more specific classes available that engage the same ideas in much more interesting, digestible ways than a big lecture that meets in section once a week.
I would if they are very disciplined and willing to sit through the lectures. I did find section a great breath of fresh air, so I'd definitely recommend going to section

If you're certain about taking the ER&M major, I would recommend taking the class later in your college career. It sounds counter-intuitive, but I think taking this class after you already have a few ER&M classes under your belt will help you make the most of this class. Otherwise, if you're not planning on taking the ER&M major, then this class is a perfect introduction and survey to the themes of the major!
Yes, it is a good course to take if youre interested fin race or applying it to another subject

I would recommend this course to another student. Especially for STEM majors, this course is useful exposure to thinking about and discussing several important topics. The professor and TAs were all super nice and understanding, and they made it a joy to take the class.

I would definitely recommend this course to any Yale student because it certainly challenges you to rethink common perceptions of the world and its history. We also learn about topics like Chinese exclusion and discrimination, the migrant workers' movement, U.S. imperialism, etc. that are typically glossed over or left out of a regular high school curriculum, so it definitely fills in the gap and provides a dissenting perspective to the history typically taught in schools.
Its required
Probably not. I think the format and level of engagement is not equivalent with other ER&M courses offered here
Yes, everyone should take this course. I cant think of a single person who wouldnt benefit from it.
yes

very interesting topics but the course is not super engaging. prof camacho's lectures often feel like a podcast where i don't need to be 100% engaged, but can still grasp most of the material. discussion sections weren't the most helpful, might benefit from more interactive activities / opportunities to talk in smaller groups within the section. pretty low workload, but
No - I took it because it was required for ER&M. Its not engaging and you can probably get more out of a similar er&m class, especially a smaller and more engaging seminar-style class.
I would recommend this course to a student wanting to know more about ER&M as a field of study or to a student who plans to major in ER&M.
